1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,740
There are some rules of thumb when looking at correlation coefficients.

2

00:00:04,740  -->  00:00:08,323
However, this is a highly field-dependent measure.

3

00:00:08,323  -->  00:00:10,271
In the social sciences,

4

00:00:10,272  -->  00:00:15,070
it can be very hard to find strong relationships because humans are complex.

5

00:00:15,070  -->  00:00:17,640
So the boundaries for the correlation coefficient for

6

00:00:17,640  -->  00:00:20,640
this field tend to be very different than say,

7

00:00:20,640  -->  00:00:23,530
the environmental associations that we find.

8

00:00:23,530  -->  00:00:26,995
So again, this is just a rule of thumb.

9

00:00:26,995  -->  00:00:31,185
If a correlation coefficient is between 1 and 0.7,

10

00:00:31,184  -->  00:00:34,259
or between negative 1 and negative 0.7,

11

00:00:34,259  -->  00:00:37,198
this is considered a strong relationship.

12

00:00:37,200  -->  00:00:40,380
If it's between 0.7 and 0.3,

13

00:00:40,380  -->  00:00:42,679
or negative 0.7 and negative 0.3,

14

00:00:42,679  -->  00:00:46,798
this is considered a moderate relationship.

15

00:00:46,798  -->  00:00:49,152
And if the absolute value is below 0.3,

16

00:00:49,152  -->  00:00:53,070
then this is considered a weak relationship.

17

00:00:53,070  -->  00:00:59,344
Remember, a negative correlation coefficient is not indicative of a weak relationship.

18

00:00:59,344  -->  00:01:02,310
Additionally, a plot can assist in

19

00:01:02,310  -->  00:01:06,189
better understanding the relationships between two variables.

20

00:01:06,188  -->  00:01:10,063
If we take two of the images from Anscombe's quartet,

21

00:01:10,063  -->  00:01:14,983
notice that these two data sets have the exact same correlation coefficient.

22

00:01:14,983  -->  00:01:18,000
However they look very different.
